<div id="pf1cdb" class="pf w33 h1e0" data-page-no="1cdb"><div class="pc pc1cdb w33 h1e0"><div class="t mb7c x10 h87 y2384 ff1 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Lesson 8 for November 21, 1936 </div><div class="t m377 xc5 h2f y20ba ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">DAILY LESSON STUDY: Place a check mark in the proper space. </div><div class="t mc8d x17 h2f ycce ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">SUNDAY </div><div class="t m5 x60 h2f y1fd8 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0"></div><div class="t m1b3b x53 h2f ycce ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">MONDAY </div><div class="t m3aa3 x85 h25 ycfb ff4 fs9 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">I </div><div class="t m36e7 x40 h2f ycfb ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">TUESDAY </div><div class="t m296d x1d h25 ye76 ff4 fs9 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">I </div><div class="t m226b x68 h2f yda8 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">WEDNESDAY </div><div class="t m3b43 x8f h25 y6f7 ff4 fs9 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">I </div><div class="t m1e82 x20 h2f y6f7 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">THURSDAY </div><div class="t m3aa3 x23 h25 y6f7 ff4 fs9 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">I </div><div class="t m2157 x91 h2f y6f7 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">FRIDAY </div><div class="t m3b43 x67 h25 yda8 ff4 fs9 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">I </div><div class="t mcd4 xef h2f y1612 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">SABBATH </div><div class="t m74c x40 h31 ycfd ff1 fs17 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Sin and Its Penalty </div><div class="t m1ae x92 h2f yca9 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">MEMORY VERSE: &quot;Wherefore, as by one man sin entered into the world, and </div><div class="t m37c x71 h2f y11d3 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">death by sin; and so death passed upon all men, for that all have sinned.&quot; Rom. 5:12. </div><div class="t mf2c x92 h2f ye61 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">STUDY HELPS: &quot;Patriarchs and Prophets,&quot; p. 67; &quot;The </div><div class="t m2ef3 xac he y7cb ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Great </div><div class="t m114 xa2 h2f y7cb ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Controversy,&quot; pp. </div><div class="t m3dd x71 h2f y128b ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">483-491; &quot;Early Writings,&quot; pp. 145, 146. </div><div class="t mb36 x51 h87 yf25 ff1 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Origin and Nature of Sin </div><div class="t m48b x26 h1 y7ee ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">1. </div><div class="t maa3 x74 h1 ya8b ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">By how many did sin enter this earth? Rom. 5:12. </div><div class="t m87a x18 he yd1d ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">NorE.—&quot;Many who teach that the law of God is not binding upon man, </div><div class="t m9a1 x15 he y6cf ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">urge that it is impossible for him to obey its precepts. But if this were true, </div><div class="t m6b9 x92 he yd57 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">why did Adam suffer the penalty of transgression? The sin of our first </div><div class="t m45b x92 he y154a ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">parents brought guilt and sorrow upon the world, and had it not been for the </div><div class="t mdf5 x92 he y9f3 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">goodness and mercy of God, would have plunged the race into hopeless despair. </div><div class="t m253 x92 he y56b ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Let none deceive themselves. &apos;The wages of sin is death.&apos; The law of God can </div><div class="t mce8 x15 he y981 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">no more be transgressed with impunity now than when sentence was pro-</div><div class="t m810 x15 he y7d5 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">nounced upon the father of </div><div class="t mfda x9c h16 y113e ff6 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">mankind.&quot;—&quot;Patriarchs and Prophets,&quot; p. 61. </div><div class="t mae7 x18 h1 yd5b ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">2. </div><div class="t m84d x74 h1 yec9 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">How is sin defined? What law is here referred to? 1 John 3:4; </div><div class="t m133d x92 h1 yaad ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">James 2:9-12. </div><div class="t m308 x18 h1 y14ac ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">3. </div><div class="t ma4b x74 h1 y121d ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">What entered that the offense might abound? When and where </div><div class="t m117a x92 h1 yee1 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">did the offense first abound? Rom. 5:20, 17, 19. </div><div class="t m486 x18 h1 y56f ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">4. </div><div class="t m8bb x74 h1 ybd7 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">What indicates that the law of God was known before it was </div><div class="t m74c x92 h1 y844 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">given in written form on Mount Sinai? Gen. 26:5; Ex. 16:28. </div><div class="t m486 x18 h1 y157e ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">5. </div><div class="t m155 x74 h1 y102a ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Under what circumstances was sin first referred to by name? </div><div class="t m13ad x92 h1 y934 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Gen. 4:7. </div><div class="t m326 x26 h1 y4ed ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">6. </div><div class="t mf6f x74 h1 y4ed ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">With whom did sin originate in heaven? Ezek. 28:14, 16; Ex. 25:20. </div><div class="t me7 x18 he y9c0 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">NorE.—&quot;Sin originated with him, who, next to Christ, had been most </div><div class="t m1d7 x92 he y15a5 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">honored of God, and was highest in power and glory among the inhabitants of </div><div class="t m7f6 x92 he ycdc ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">heaven. Lucifer, &apos;son of the morning,&apos; was first of the covering cherubs, holy </div><div class="t md00 x92 he yf4b ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">and undefiled. He stood in the presence of the great Creator, and the ceaseless </div><div class="t m68f x92 he y47c ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">beams of glory enshrouding the eternal God, rested upon </div><div class="t m1912 xc9 h16 y1223 ff6 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">him.&quot;—Id., p. 35. </div><div class="t m25c x6a h87 yd15 ff1 fs7 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Results of Sin </div><div class="t m486 x18 h1 y93d ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">7. </div><div class="t m608 x74 h1 yd66 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">What did Lucifer&apos;s sin lead God do? Ezek. 28:17; Rev. 12:7-9. </div><div class="t m43c x18 he yd47 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">NOTE.—No place was &quot;found any more in heaven&quot; for Lucifer and his </div><div class="t m6a6 x92 he yd2d ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">angels. They had forfeited their right to the purity and joy of heaven and </div><div class="t m633 x92 he y7a1 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">association with its sinless inhabitants. </div><div class="t mdcf x18 h1 y5ac ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">8. </div><div class="t m8a8 x74 h1 y5ac ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">What loss did Adam and Eve sustain because of transgression? </div><div class="t m1ada x92 h1 ya23 ff1 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Gen. 3:22-24. </div><div class="t m1127 x18 he yfbf ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">NOTE.—&quot;After their sin, Adam and Eve were no longer to dwell in Eden. </div><div class="t mc9 x92 he ye15 ff4 fs0 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">They earnestly entreated that they might remain in the home of their innocency </div><div class="t m306 x98 h2f y12e2 ff4 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">[24 </div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.000000,0.000000,0.000000,1.000000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
